Customer reviews4.6 out of 5 stars4.6 out of 5 43 global ratings 5 star 73% 4 star 15% 3 star 9% 2 star 4% 1 star 0% (0%) 0% How customer reviews and ratings work Customer Reviews, including Product Star Ratings help customers to learn more about the product and decide whether it is the right product for them. To calculate the overall star rating and percentage breakdown by star, we don’t use a simple average. Instead, our system considers things like how recent a review is and if the reviewer bought the item on Amazon. It also analyzed reviews to verify trustworthiness. Learn more how customers reviews work on Amazon Top reviews Most recent Top reviews Top reviews from the United States There was a problem filtering reviews right now. Please try again later.Rich P.5.0 out of 5 stars Im impressed. Pro sound. Nice construction. GREAT price. Reviewed in the United States on March 17, 2016Style: 4-Piece Drum PackVerified Purchase I used this set on March 11, 2016 for the Mike Zito and the Wheel show I produced and also did sound for. I have another set of Audix FP4 mics but wanted a newer set than what I had and wanted to try the CAD set on recommendation of a friend of mine. They are built like a set that costs 3 times as much. The kick mic is approx the size and weight of a Shure Beta 52. The others are a nice compact size and mount quickly on the drum head ring. All the mics sounded wonderful that night. The kick mic is very accurate and supplies plenty of punch. I run a Peavey Kosmos on the kick channel to clarify and add sub-harmonics to the kick signal after the gate. It took very little to liven up the kick. The snare and tom mics are pretty much on it too with just a slight upper mid range boost curve around 4k but was corrected with the drum mix eq. The drum mix came through loud and clear without a hitch.All-in-all I guess for the price, construction and sound these are a great choice for your sound system. That night was a small to medium room around 200-225 people and I used 2 large custom 18" sub cabs and 2 Peavey SP5 BX's for the front sound and all Yamaha BR M12 stage monitors run with various Peavey CS amps. Read more 3 people found this helpful Helpful Report abuse Chad2.0 out of 5 stars Ehh..they will do.. Reviewed in the United States on August 17, 2015Style: 4-Piece Drum PackVerified Purchase These mics work great. They do have a design flaw with the clamps. If your using stick saver rims they will wobble loose because they won't tighten down no matter how hard to torque them. When you're able to place these mics on your drums rims firmly you're unable to get the correct angle with the mic. You may be better off getting these mics and figuring out a way to apply a different clamp. Also, because of vibration the mic itself will tend to unscrew, opening up completely. Props for them "doing the job" but they're basically just a stepping stone and gives you a chance to be in the mains while you put away cash to get something better. I will be going with something better in the future, but until then I will have to deal with it. Read more 2 people found this helpful Helpful Report abuse S. Brock4.0 out of 5 stars Great Value Reviewed in the United States on August 17, 2019Style: 4-Piece Drum PackVerified Purchase Not quite as nice as an SM57, but these mics get the job done. I tweaked them a bit with a WAVES plug in and it sounds great. The one con is the fact that they have to clip to the drum (except the bass drum mic) and cannot be put on a mic stand, but so far that has worked with no issues. Really glad I got these and didn't spend a ton of money. Read more Helpful Report abuse jeffrey A5.0 out of 5 stars Excellent value Reviewed in the United States on August 10, 2021Style: 4-Piece Drum PackVerified Purchase Hard to beat these for the money. I have better sounding mics, but not at this price point.Are they Shure Betas? No, but they preform well. Read more Helpful Report abuse Steven M.5.0 out of 5 stars Can't go wrong for the price. Reviewed in the United States on December 16, 2015Style: 4-Piece Drum PackVerified Purchase So much bang for your buck here. I play in a garage band, nothing crazy serious. For what we do these mics are perfect. Worth checking out if you're having issues with your current mic situation. Read more One person found this helpful Helpful Report abuse Undercover Drummer3.0 out of 5 stars Not for the professional musician. Reviewed in the United States on October 9, 2016Style: 4-Piece Drum PackVerified Purchase Clips are cheap, had to duct tape them to the hoops to keep them tight. Used these one gig, then purchased the Shure package with 3 sm57 mics and the Beta 52A for the kick. Cost 3 times as much but the mic clamps that come in the Shure are worth the money alone. Sold these on another site for 60 bucks. If you have the cash buy the Shure's. Read more 3 people found this helpful Helpful Report abuse Arjun Kaul5.0 out of 5 stars Used it last night and they're good! Reviewed in the United States on July 19, 2013Style: 4-Piece Drum PackVerified Purchase Used this in a club gig last night and they really shone. Our drum setup only has 2 toms so this set is just perfect.The sound quality and overal output from these is nice and full. Had no problems with feedback either. Kick drum mic gives that nice deep kick sound. Snare mic gives a good full forward sounding snare sound. A little tweaking at the mixer and you're good to go.Buy with confidence. When you're able to place these mics on your drums rims firmly you're unable to get the correct angle with the mic. You may be better off getting these mics and figuring out a way to apply a different clamp. Also, because of vibration the mic itself will tend to unscrew, opening up completely. Props for them "doing the job" but they're basically just a stepping stone and gives you a chance to be in the mains while you put away cash to get something better. The kick mic is very accurate and supplies plenty of punch. I run a Peavey Kosmos on the kick channel to clarify and add sub-harmonics to the kick signal after the gate. It took very little to liven up the kick. The snare and tom mics are pretty much on it too with just a slight upper mid range boost curve around 4k but was corrected with the drum mix eq. The drum mix came through loud and clear without a hitch.All-in-all I guess for the price, construction and sound these are a great choice for your sound system. That night was a small to medium room around 200-225 people and I used 2 large custom 18" sub cabs and 2 Peavey SP5 BX's for the front sound and all Yamaha BR M12 stage monitors run with various Peavey CS amps. Chad2.0 out of 5 stars Ehh..they will do.. Reviewed in the United States on August 17, 2015Style: 4-Piece Drum PackVerified Purchase These mics work great. They do have a design flaw with the clamps. If your using stick saver rims they will wobble loose because they won't tighten down no matter how hard to torque them. When you're able to place these mics on your drums rims firmly you're unable to get the correct angle with the mic. You may be better off getting these mics and figuring out a way to apply a different clamp. Also, because of vibration the mic itself will tend to unscrew, opening up completely. Props for them "doing the job" but they're basically just a stepping stone and gives you a chance to be in the mains while you put away cash to get something better. I will be going with something better in the future, but until then I will have to deal with it. Read more 2 people found this helpful Helpful Report abuse
